Who I am and where I came from

I am originally from Illinois, but I went to school in at George Washignton University in Washington DC and after that lived in my car around Jackson WY for 2 months. That’s where I got really into rock climbing, especially alpine climbing, which is what really drives me (besides research). I always knew I wanted to go back to graduate school but wasn’t sure what I wanted to study until I discovered Rosy Finches while hiking up on the Middle Teton one afternoon. Researching those birds brought me to Kristen Ruegg’s lab and to CSU. I’m taking this class now because my work requires lots of bioinformatics skills and although I’ve been trudging alone learning as best I can I thought I more structured class would be helpful.

Some of my favorite things to do are: 1. Rock climbing of any sort 2. Adventuring with my dog 3. Reading 4. Painting

Here’s a picture of me and my dog, Juniper.

Research Interests

I’m interested in understanding how the evolution of local adaptation is impacted Rosy Finch species ability to adapt to climate change.

Influential papers

Bay R, Harrigan RJ, Underwood VL, Gibbs HL, Smith TB, Ruegg K. 2018. Genomic signals of selection predict climate-driven population declines. Science:83-89. (Bay et al. 2018)

Bay et al. (2018) is a great paper that introduced me to the type of conservation genomics that is done is Kristen’s lab and that I am learning how to do. This paper asseses the genomic vulnerability of yellow warbler populations and determines genes that are important to this species ability to adapt to climate change.

Drovetski SV, Zink RM, Mode NA. 2009. Patchy distributions belie morphological and genetic homogeneity in rosy-finches. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 50:437-445. (Drovetski, Zink, and Mode 2009)

Drovetski, Zink, and Mode (2009) was one of the first papers I read about Rosy Finches back when I was just getting into them, and also one of the few papers that applies genetics (in this case phylogenetics) to this group of species. The authors tease apart the phylogenetic relationships between different species of Rosy Finch.

The mathematics behind my research

This first equation is the mathematical writing of how you would get a estimate of local adaptation using the “home vs away” definition of local adaptation, per Blanquart et al. (2013). \[ \Delta_{HA} (i)= \overline{W}_{i\to i} - \frac{1}{P-1} \displaystyle \sum\limits_{\substack{j=1 \\ j\neq 1}} \overline{W}_{i-j} \] This is an equation for effective population size: Ne = 4NmNf/(Nm + Nf) \[ N_e = \frac{4N_m N_f}{N_m + N_f} \]

I’m also used to doing stuff in R (largely from a landscape ecology course I took my first year, shout of to Kyle Horton). Here’s a little chunk of me running a t.test on some morphological data.

morpho <- read.csv("~/Desktop/GCRF/R data/GCRF_morphology.csv")
nare <- as.data.frame(cbind(morpho$site, morpho$BGP_ID, morpho$nare_length))
colnames(nare) <- c("site", "BGP_ID", "measure")

nare <- na.omit(nare)
a <- c(62, 67, 70, 78, 83, 84, 89, 93, 94, 95, 96)
nare <- nare[-a,]
nare$measure <- as.numeric(nare$measure)

#super significant two way test! p=3.23e-06
t.test(measure ~ site, data=nare)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  measure by site
## t = 4.8936, df = 86.769, p-value = 4.526e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group PIPA and group WMNT is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1929648 0.4569484
## sample estimates:
## mean in group PIPA mean in group WMNT 
##           2.199709           1.874752
